E. COLI EHEC - CANADA (02): (ONTARIO) RECREATIONAL AREA
*******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 18 Sep 2020 18:27 EDT
Source: Global News [edited]
https://globalnews.ca/news/7344942/e-coli-cases-valens-lake/


Hamilton Public Health is confirming an _E. coli_ outbreak at Valens Lake Conservation Area. The city's public health unit says there are 7 confirmed cases at the Puslinch-area conservation area, with one of the cases involving a Hamilton resident. Public health says most of the confirmed cases involve children under the age of 12.

_E. coli_ is transmitted most commonly through consumption of contaminated food or water. Common symptoms of the bacteria can include diarrhea, fever, vomiting and abdominal cramps, but _E. coli_ can also lead to life-threatening disease, including hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS), especially in young children and the elderly.

Residents who have visited Valens Lake Conservation Area since 12 Aug 2020 and are concerned about possible illness, are asked to contact their primary care physician or the Public Health Infectious Disease Program at 905-546-2063. The beach at Valens Lake Conservation Area is closed as of Friday [18 Sep 2020] to mitigate any further exposure to the bacteria. Public health says visitors to Valens should not swim in the water and residents looking to engage in secondary recreation activities, such as kayaking or canoeing, can do so at their own risk.

[Byline: Ken Mann]

