Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is not stated but likely that the organism in this outbreak is one of the enterohemorrhagic strains of _E. coli_, zoonotic organisms that are acquired from contaminated food or water. Valens Lake Conservation Area is a large recreational area in Ontario for camping, fishing and other outdoor activities. It is not clear as yet what epidemiological factors link those affected, as there could be a common food or food source or the recreational water could be the source.

EHEC is most often associated with undercooked ground beef or other contaminated food; the disease can also be transmitted when people drink, or swim in, tainted water. The primary carriers are cattle but can be deer, sheep, goats, other livestock or wild animals or humans. In the spring of 2000, in Walkerton, a town of 5000 in southern Ontario, an outbreak of _E. coli_ O157:H7 infection claimed 7 lives -- 6 adults and a child -- and over 200 were seen at local area hospitals.

Swimming-associated transmission is illustrated in the following references:

1. Keene WE, McAnulty JM, Hoesly FC, et al. A swimming-associated outbreak of hemorrhagic colitis caused by _Escherichia coli_ O157:H7 and _Shigella sonnei_. N Engl J Med. 1994; 331(9): 579-84. http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJM199409013310904
2. CDC. Lake-associated outbreak of _E. coli_ O157:H7 - Illinois. MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep. 1996; 45(21): 437-9. https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00042070.htm
3. Ackman D, Marks S, Mack P, et al. Swimming-associated hemorrhagic colitis due to _Escherichia coli_ O157:H7 infection: evidence of prolonged contamination of a fresh water lake. Epidemiol Infect. 1997; 119: 1-8. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2808815/
- Mod.LL

